Maybe a fisheye lens is a bit too much for a birdhouse.
One never learns.
I should have known better, since I already built one with a "normal" lens once before.
I will write more about it over the weekend as soon as I have the second one installed.
Let's just say that the birds will have a better internet connection than I did in 2015.
At least, that's the plan.
The box in which there is already a nest is sucking up a lot of Wi-Fi data.
It becomes a bit more difficult for him to go online.
Okay, I've hung the new nesting box up today. That's what it looks like in its new place in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. Nobody asks: "What's exactly in there?"
Above is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera that has a fisheye lens and an IR LED, which I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swinging side wall of the nesting box. I bought it like this and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Because there is no power in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
In the grey box, which hangs beside the nest box, is the battery.
When it's fully charged, I have a battery life of about 4 hours.
That's a feature. So the birds get some privacy as well.
At the beginning I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be enough for this setup. The old access points I replaced last fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new covers this area very well.
That's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and set it up in the garden below.
Maybe I'll do that if I set up more nesting boxes with cameras. I probably need that, especially in areas further away from the house.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It shut off just an hour after sunset.
Possibly the battery did not continue to charge three hours before sunset because there was not enough light.
Or something less than half a day was too little to fully charge the battery.
I suppose I'll have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I may have to change that in the future.
In general, having a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And perhaps a battery that can at least theoretically keep the thing running overnight.
Yes, and another lens.
The fisheye is quite exaggerated.
But I'm already looking for components on Digikey so that I can build my own board exactly for that.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And he is still offline.
That's great.
According to the actual solar panels on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens – or doesn't.
Still offline.
It's never easy, is it.
It turned out that 5 V and GND were swapped on the Silkscreen of the USB-C Breakout I used to connect the charger.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lit.
The ESP did not go online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and he's still offline.
Looks like he's starting over and triggering a Tasmota reset.
I think the panel just doesn't do anything. I've now ordered a bigger one and hope that will work then.
Look what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partially blocked by a tree), that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I put the device into operation.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if it's enough for this setup or if I need the better panel that I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it is supposed to deliver 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
Either something is wrong with the panel or with my multimeter, or the data has been altered.
Good news!
They changed the data, and the ones I have are incorrect.
The old as well as the new listing title calls it a 12 V 10-W panel.
Therefore, I never delete old e-mails.
Oh look! The thing went offline about an hour ago, and is back online for roughly half a minute.
Maybe the panel has just charged the battery long enough for a 38-second runtime. It took only a bit more than two hours to do so.
Guess what: Today it's cloudy. I'm therefore not sure if the (likely broken) solar panel will even be able to generate enough power.
Wait patiently.
Update: I have installed the new panel and it now seems to be working.
It could still work out as soon as the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Funfact: I use the Ping-Integration in Home Assistant to see if it's online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but not incredibly bad either.
